What:		/sys/kernel/gia/
Date:		February 2025
Contact:	Chintan Pandya <chintanpandya@google.com>
Description:
		The `/sys/kernel/gia/` directory contains subdirectories, one for
		each GIA-enabled device present in the system. The names of these
		subdirectories (e.g., `dpu-level-aggr-20-intr@ef88000`) are
		device-specific and provide a unique identifier for each GIA instance.

What:		/sys/kernel/gia/<device-name>/gia_count
Date:		February 2025
Contact:	Chintan Pandya <chintanpandya@google.com>
Description:
		The `gia_count` file represents the total number of GIA
		(Generic Interrupt Accelerator) events handled by the
		specified device. This is a monotonically increasing counter.
		The value is a decimal integer.

What:		/sys/kernel/gia/<device-name>/gia_handler_latency_min
Date:		February 2025
Contact:	Chintan Pandya <chintanpandya@google.com>
Description:
		The `gia_handler_latency_min` file represents the minimum
		latency (in nanoseconds) observed for handling a GIA event
		by the specified device. This value represents the time
		taken by GIA specific handler. It's an unsigned integer.

What:		/sys/kernel/gia/<device-name>/gia_handler_latency_max
Date:		February 2025
Contact:	Chintan Pandya <chintanpandya@google.com>
Description:
		The `gia_handler_latency_max` file represents the maximum
		latency (in nanoseconds) observed for handling a GIA event
		by the specified device. This value represents the time
		taken by GIA specific handler. It's an unsigned integer.

What:		/sys/kernel/gia/<device-name>/gia_handler_latency_avg
Date:		February 2025
Contact:	Chintan Pandya <chintanpandya@google.com>
Description:
		The `gia_handler_latency_avg` file represents the average
		latency (in nanoseconds) observed for handling GIA events
		by the specified device. This value represents the time
		taken by GIA specific handler. This is an unsigned long long
		integer. Reads may return 0 if no events have occurred.

What:		/sys/kernel/gia/<device-name>/gia_concurrency_<n>
Date:		February 2025
Contact:	Chintan Pandya <chintanpandya@google.com>
Description:
		Files of the form `gia_concurrency_<n>` (where <n> is a positive integer,
		starting from 1 and goes till 4, represent data related to GIA concurrency.
		The specific meaning of the data within each `gia_concurrency_<n>` file
		is how many time <n> interrupts occurred. These files are read-only.

What:		/sys/kernel/gia/<device-name>/hwirq_<n>/
Date:		February 2025
Contact:	Chintan Pandya <chintanpandya@google.com>
Description:
		The `/sys/kernel/gia/<device-name>/hwirq_<n>/` directory contains
		statistics and information related to a specific hardware interrupt
		line, identified by `<n>`, associated with the GIA device
		`<device-name>`.  `<n>` is a zero-padded, three-digit decimal
		number (e.g., `hwirq_007`, `hwirq_012`). There will be a directory
		of this form for each hardware interrupt managed by the GIA device.

What:		/sys/kernel/gia/<device-name>/hwirq_<n>/irq_count
Date:		February 2025
Contact:	Chintan Pandya <chintanpandya@google.com>
Description:
		The `irq_count` file represents the total number of times hardware
		interrupt `<n>` (associated with the GIA device) has been triggered.
		This is a monotonically increasing counter.  The value is a decimal
		integer.

What:		/sys/kernel/gia/<device-name>/hwirq_<n>/irq_handler_time_min
Date:		February 2025
Contact:	Chintan Pandya <chintanpandya@google.com>
Description:
		The `irq_handler_time_min` file represents the minimum latency
		(in nanoseconds) observed for handling hardware interrupt `<n>`.
		This is the time spent in the interrupt handler itself.
		It's an unsigned integer.

What:		/sys/kernel/gia/<device-name>/hwirq_<n>/irq_handler_time_max
Date:		February 2025
Contact:	Chintan Pandya <chintanpandya@google.com>
Description:
		The `irq_handler_time_max` file represents the maximum latency
		(in nanoseconds) observed for handling hardware interrupt `<n>`.
		This is the time spent in the interrupt handler itself.
		It's an unsigned integer.

What:		/sys/kernel/gia/<device-name>/hwirq_<n>/irq_handler_time_avg
Date:		February 2025
Contact:	Chintan Pandya <chintanpandya@google.com>
Description:
		The `irq_handler_time_avg` file represents the average latency
		(in nanoseconds) observed for handling hardware interrupt `<n>`.
		This is the time spent in the interrupt handler itself.
		It's an unsigned long long integer.  Reads may return 0 if no
		interrupts have occurred.

What:		/sys/kernel/gia/<device-name>/hwirq_<n>/irq_max_freq
Date:		February 2025
Contact:	Chintan Pandya <chintanpandya@google.com>
Description:
		The `irq_max_freq` file represents the maximum frequency (in Hz)
		at which hardware interrupt `<n>` has been observed. This gives
		an indication of the peak interrupt rate. It is represented as a decimal
		integer.

What:		/sys/kernel/gia/<device-name>/hwirq_<n>/irq_name
Date:		February 2025
Contact:	Chintan Pandya <chintanpandya@google.com>
Description:
		The `irq_name` file contains a string representing the name
		assigned to hardware interrupt `<n>`. This is typically a
		descriptive name provided by the device driver.

What:		/sys/kernel/gia/<device-name>/hwirq_<n>/irq_sw_wait_time_min
Date:		February 2025
Contact:	Chintan Pandya <chintanpandya@google.com>
Description:
		The `irq_sw_wait_time_min` file represents the minimum software
		wait time (in nanoseconds) observed for hardware interrupt `<n>`.
		This is the time spent waiting in software, before the interrupt
		handler can proceed. It's an unsigned integer.

What:		/sys/kernel/gia/<device-name>/hwirq_<n>/irq_sw_wait_time_max
Date:		February 2025
Contact:	Chintan Pandya <chintanpandya@google.com>
Description:
		The `irq_sw_wait_time_max` file represents the maximum software
		wait time (in nanoseconds) observed for hardware interrupt `<n>`.
		This is the time spent waiting in software, before the interrupt
		handler can proceed. It's an unsigned integer.

What:		/sys/kernel/gia/<device-name>/hwirq_<n>/irq_sw_wait_time_avg
Date:		February 2025
Contact:	Chintan Pandya <chintanpandya@google.com>
Description:
		The `irq_sw_wait_time_avg` file represents the average software
		wait time (in nanoseconds) observed for hardware interrupt `<n>`.
		This is the time spent waiting in software, before the interrupt
		handler can proceed. It's an unsigned integer.

What:		/sys/kernel/gia/<device-name>/hwirq_<n>/irq_virq
Date:		February 2025
Contact:	Chintan Pandya <chintanpandya@google.com>
Description:
		The `irq_virq` file represents the virtual interrupt number
		associated with hardware interrupt `<n>`. This is a decimal integer.
